<FILEID>AP-NR-12-27-89 0117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SECEnforcement Bjt   12-27 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC Enforcement, Bjt,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Creates New Fraud Unit to Protect Small Investors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission,
catapulted into the headlines by its pursuit of multimillion-dollar
insider trading scandals, is putting out the word that it intends
to be just as aggressive in protecting small investors.
   SEC Chairman Richard Breeden is creating a new fraud unit at the
SEC designed to police the sale of securities by savings and loan
institutions.
   Investigators have charged that some small investors lost their
life savings when they bought securities sold by S&amp;L branches in
the mistaken belief that their investments were protected by
federal deposit insurance.
   ``We intend to see to it that when people are sold securities,
they are provided all the necessary information,'' Breeden said.
   Breeden also announced Tuesday that he had selected William R.
McLucas, a 12-year SEC veteran, to be the new director of
enforcement at the SEC. He will succeed Gary Lynch, who resigned in
July after supervising such landmark insider trading cases as the
investigation of Ivan Boesky and the Wall Street firm of Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Both Breeden and McLucas stressed that insider trading still
would be a top SEC priority, but they also indicated that the SEC,
with a 20 percent increase in its budget, would devote more
resources to more low-profile crooks.
   ``Where there is an abuse of a customer's trust, those are the
kinds of cases where we are going to make sure we have an impact,''
McLucas said at a news conference where his selection was announced.
   Individual investors have been leaving the market in droves in
recent years, scared off in part by extreme trading volatility.
Many officials believe the SEC must return to its primary mission
of bolstering confidence in financial markets through protection of
the small investor.
   Breeden, who was picked for the SEC post by President Bush last
summer, said both the administration and Congress had expressed a
strong desire to crack down on abuses against individual investors.
Breeden noted that Congress approved a 20 percent increase in the
SEC budget this year, enough to allow the agency to hire 100 more
attorneys.
   Part of the increased staffing will be used, Breeden said, to
create a special 25-attorney unit to investigate overly aggressive
sales of securities by savings and loans and other financial
institutions.
   Such sales became a major focus of congressional hearings into
the activities at Lincoln Savings and Loan Association, the Irvine,
Calif.-based S&amp;L whose failure is expected to end up costing
taxpayers a record $2 billion.
   Small investors told congressional investigators they were lured
into purchasing bonds in Lincoln Savings' parent company, American
Continental Corp., in the mistaken belief that their money was
protected by federal deposit insurance.
   When American Continental, which is headed by Arizona
businessman Charles H. Keating Jr., filed for protection under the
bankruptcy law, it left some 22,000 small investors who had
purchased nearly $200 million in corporate bonds in the lurch.
   Breeden said the new SEC unit will try to prevent financially
ailing S&amp;Ls from turning to fraudulent practices in a desperate
effort to raise cash.
   McLucas, 39, joined the SEC in 1977, two years after receiving a
law degree from Temple University.
   Lynch, who resigned to join a New York law firm, served for four
years as SEC enforcement chief, taking over from John Fedders, who
was forced to resign after allegations surfaced that he had beaten
his wife.
   Lynch was credited with restoring morale at the SEC and
directing some of the agency's biggest investigations, beginning
with the exposure of Dennis Levine in May 1986. Levine's
cooperation led to a $100 million settlement with speculator Ivan
Boesky. Boesky in turn implicated Drexel Burnham, which led to a
$650 million settlement with the securities firm, the largest
securities fraud case ever brought by the government.
   Civil and criminal charges are still pending against former
Drexel junk bond pioneer Michael Milken.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891227-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-27-89 0118EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Panama-Democracy     12-27 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Democracy,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lack of Democratic Tradition in Panama Stymies US Efforts, Scholars
Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. presidents since Teddy Roosevelt in 1903
have talked about the need to install democracy in Panama. Some
sent troops under the banner of shoring up democratic rule.
   But all have been stymied by the lack of democratic tradition in
the strategically placed isthmus and by their overriding desire to
protect U.S. rights of passage through the Panama Canal, scholars
say.
   When President Bush went on television Wednesday morning to
explain why he dispatched troops to remove Panamanian strongman
Manuel Antonio Noriega from power, he cited the Panamanian people's
desire for democracy and peace. ``The people of the United States
seek only to support them in pursuit of these noble goals,'' he
said.
   ``The rhetoric about favoring democracy is no more than that.
It's a pretense,'' said John Peeler, who heads the Center for the
Study of the Americas at Bucknell University in Pennsylvania.
   The real U.S. desire is ``for democratic government, read
reliable government, one that won't threaten our control of the
canal,'' Peeler added.
   The few times in their 86-year history of independence when
Panamanians have supported a truly democratic government, ``We
weren't willing to accept their choice,'' Peeler said.
   That includes Arnulfo Arias, a populist leader elected president
twice in the 1940s and again in 1968. Arias' left-leaning views did
not sit well with the United States, which was not sorry to see him
ousted after several days in office by National Guard commander
Gen. Omar Torrijos.
   But Torrijos proved an even bigger problem for the
administration, with his pro-Cuban policies and strong nationalism
which opposed the U.S. right under the 1903 treaty to use the canal
``in perpetuity.''
   Increasing friction with the United States led to the
ratification of a new treaty in 1978 ceding the canal to Panama in
the year 2000 but reserving the right to intervene if shipping
through the waterway were threatened.
   Threats to U.S. use of the canal were what prompted the first
dispatch of military force to Panama. When Colombia, which ruled
Panama in the 19th Century, refused to approve the 1903 canal
treaty with the United States, Roosevelt sent warships to help the
growing Panamanian secessionist movement.
   But the warships only stood by as the secessionists launched a
bloodless revolt and declared independence.
   In August 1914, the same month World War I broke out, the first
ships passed through the canal. But political chaos reigned and the
United States sent troops to register voters and supervise
elections.
   Each time that happened _ in 1908, 1912 and 1916 _ the losing
side blamed U.S. interference.
   By the 1930s, ``there was growing U.S. frustration with the
attempts to instill democracy in Panama,'' said Frank Gerome, a
professor of history at James Madison University in Virginia.
Gerome has written extensively about U.S. efforts to organize the
1912 elections.
   Panama's strategic importance grew immensely in World War II,
when the U.S. military presence rose sharply to defend oil
shipments from Venezuela to the United States against German
interception. The hitherto limited U.S. military presence, which
had been centered mostly around the canal, spread to other parts of
the country.
   Panama in the 1950s and 1960s was ruled by a succession of
families from among a thin elite. While not a military state,
neither was it truly democratic.
   Torrijos' rise to power in 1968 transferred power to the
military, with a nominal role for civilian governments. Such was
the setup under Noriega, too, after Torrijos died in a 1981 plane
crash.
   ``Various American presidents hoped the roots of democracy might
grow,'' said Gerome. ``What they failed to understand is that you
can't export democracy.''
   Noriega, abhorrent though he is now to the U.S. administration
which nurtured him in the 1970s, enjoyed strong popular appeal
among Panama's poor.
   Guillermo Endara, who was installed at a U.S. military facility
as Panama's president on Thursday based on the results of last
May's elections, does not enjoy Noriega's popular appeal. His main
support comes from middle-class merchants.
   ``Support for him is weak, not passionate,'' and being propped
up by the United States can only be a liability, said Peeler,
adding, ``People aren't celebrating democracy, they're looting.
Doesn't Bush see that?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
