<DOCNO> AP891227-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-27-89 2244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0690 12-27 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0690,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS Phelan and Craft. AMs separates moved on Randall as a0511;
on Garde as a0489; and on Franklin as a0675.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Walter Randall</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walter Doane ``Bo'' Randall, renowned as
one of the world's best knife makers, died Monday at age 80.
   The cause of death was not available.
   Randall, who began hand-crafting hunting knives half a century
ago as a hobby, had an eight-member factory in Orlando that turned
out knives favored by the Army's Special Forces and military men
and civilians in many countries.
   Randall knives are displayed in the Smithsonian Institution and
the Museum of Special Warfare at Fort Bragg, N.C.
   The knife-collector's bible, American Knives, called Randall the
world's greatest blade maker.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Betty Garde</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Betty Garde, who appeared in hundreds of
radio plays and portrayed Aunt Eller in the original Broadway
production of ``Oklahoma,'' died Monday at age 84.
   The cause of death was not available.
   Garde began her stage career in the early 1920s. She played
character roles in Broadway productions such as ``The Social
Register'' and ``The Primrose Path.''
   In the 1930s she moved into radio, appearing in three dozen
shows over the years, including ``The Eddie Cantor Show,'' ``Perry
Mason'' and ``The Fat Man.''
   She probably was best known as the wife of ``Lorenzo Jones'' and
as ``Mrs. Wiggs of the Cabbage Patch.''
   Garde worked on several Orson Welles radio specials and appeared
regularly in the dramatic anthology ``Theater Guild on the Air.''
   She had a few motion picture and television roles, notably as
Wanda Skutnik in the James Stewart film ``Call Northside 777.''
