<FILEID>AP-NR-12-27-89 2238EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Chevron-Pennzoil     12-27 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Chevron-Pennzoil,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Lifts Ban on Pennzoil Suits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge in Chevron Corp.'s suit
over Pennzoil Co.'s alleged clandestine takeover attempt lifted
restrictions Wednesday on Pennzoil's ability to file countersuits
in other courts.
   U.S. District Judge Thelton Henderson refused to extend an order
imposed by another federal judge Dec. 7 that prohibited Pennzoil
from suing anywhere on related issues without approval of the San
Francisco federal court.
   Henderson noted that Pennzoil had denied any intention of suing,
said Chevron's claims to the contrary were based on speculation,
and added that the local court had the power to prevent
inconsistent rulings even if other suits were filed elsewhere.
   The decision was a skirmish in Chevron's battle to force
Pennzoil to sell its newly acquired $2.1 billion, 8.8 percent share
of Chevron's stock and prohibit it from buying more stock without
court approval.
   San Francisco-based Chevron also is seeking to validate the
anti-takeover measures its directors took around the time of the
disclosure of Pennzoil's purchases three weeks ago.
   Pennzoil, based in Houston, said it was using $2.1 billion of
its $2.6 billion net proceeds from a settlement of its suit with
Texaco as a long-term investment in Chevron for tax purposes.
Pennzoil said it might invest the other $500 million in Chevron
stock but denied any intention of a takeover of the nation's
fourth-largest oil company.
   But Chevron, citing Pennzoil's past attempts to acquire oil
property, contended the rival firm intended a hostile merger or a
forced restructuring.
   Chevron's suit accuses Pennzoil of violating federal laws
requiring advance notice and a 30-day waiting period before major
stock purchases by anyone but a passive long-term investor.
   Pennzoil, saying Chevron's suit is based on unfounded
suspicions, has asked Henderson to dismiss the case. A ruling is
pending.
   Wednesday's decision involved an order Chevron obtained Dec. 7
from Chief U.S. District Judge William Ingram forbidding suits by
Pennzoil without approval from the local court.
   Chevron said Pennzoil would inevitably sue to challenge the
restrictions on takeovers, and argued that restrictions were needed
to avoid inconsistent decisions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891227-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-27-89 2332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Hilton     12-27 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hilton,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report That Bids Are Low Causes Hilton Stock Price To Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hilton Hotels Corp. stock plunged
Wednesday on a report that offers for the hotel-casino company are
in the $90 range instead of the $120 some analysts had believed
Hilton would fetch.
   Hilton, which was put up for sale last summer after the
settlement of a dispute over the estate of founder Conrad Hilton,
fell $6.87{ to close at $82.87{ a share on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   The Wall Street Journal reported that JMB Realty Corp., a
Chicago-based pension fund manager, had offered about $90 a share
for Hilton, which would bring the total offer to $4.3 billion.
Hilton general counsel William Lebo declined to comment on the
report.
   Another of the bidders for Hilton is Miller-Klutznick-Davis-Gray
Co., billionaire investor Marvin Davis' Denver-based real estate
vehicle. The Journal reported that Miller-Klutznick was bidding
about the market price for the stock, which was about $90 before
the Journal report Wednesday.
   Calls to Miller-Klutznick and JMB were not returned.
   Hilton stock was trading at $63 per share when Conrad Hilton's
son, Barron Hilton, settled the estate dispute in May.
   In August, Hilton stock soared to $112 a share on reports that
the company would consider at least two formal buyout bids. At that
time, some analysts were estimating that shareholders were likely
to get $120 per share if Hilton was sold and possibly as much as
$140.
   But the collapse of the junk bond market and fears of a
recession have made it much harder to complete takeovers recently,
and the stock price has gradually fallen as no deal was announced.
   Hilton had its best year ever in 1987, when profits rose 43
percent and earnings were $5.59 per share. Earnings fell to $2.72
per share last year and have remained relatively flat this year,
rising 2 percent in the July-September quarter to $28.1 million, or
57 cents a share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
